<TEXT>
an undertaker who grappled with an airline 
stewardess when she told him to stop smoking was ordered monday to 
spend 15 days in prison by a judge who said he wants to protect the 
flying public 
james j tabacca 34 who was convicted of interfering with a 
flight crew said he never meant to upset anyone and pleaded for 
probation 
but us district judge wallace tashima said he wanted tabaccas 
sentence to have a deterrent effect on other passengers who might 
take the law into their own hands 
he then imposed a suspended sentence of 18 months with the 
provision that tabacca spend 15 days behind bars his attorney was 
given three weeks to appeal and tabacca was ordered to report to a 
federal prison dec 4 
tabacca also was placed on two years probation fined 500 and 
ordered to perform 100 hours of community service in restitution to 
the public 
the confrontation dec 30 on a twa flight from boston to los 
angeles occurred when flight attendant pamela martinez tried to stop 
tabacca from lighting a cigarette in the nosmoking section of the 
jetliner 
tabaccas ticket was for the smoking section but most seats on 
the flight were converted to nonsmoking because of government 
regulations requiring airlines to provide nosmoking seats for all 
passengers who arrive on time and want them 
tabacca twisted ms martinez arm and shoved her across the aisle 
into the bulkhead shouting obscenities at her when she tried to 
stop him from smoking said assistant us attorney robin scroggie 
a jury convicted him sept 6 of interfering with a flight crew 
but acquitted him of assault 
he had faced a maximum penalty of 20 years in prison and a 
250000 fine 
for the safety of the flying public it is necessary that all 
passengers abide by the law of flying conduct and not take the law 
into their own hands tashima said 
because of the nature of the offense and the public nature of 
the offense some custody time is required he told tabacca 
the defendant an undertaker from north hollywood pleaded for 
leniency 
sincerely i am sorry that such an incident has ever taken 
place he said i cant believe this has happened to me i never 
meant any interruption or to upset anyone my family and i have 
suffered greatly from this 
deputy public defender kerry bensinger suggested that prison time 
was an excessive penalty 
mr tabacca is now a convicted felon he said his name has 
been published in the papers we believe that is all the 
punishment mr tabacca needs to receive 
</TEXT>
