<TEXT>
the devils disciple is the most melodramatic 
of george bernard shaws comedies a play in which the hero spends a 
good deal of the last act with a noose around his neck waiting to 
be hanged 
it requires a swashbuckler of an actor a daring doer who can 
physically dominate the stage charm the other characters as well 
as the audience and at the same time negotiate some of shaws 
wittiest and trickiest dialogue 
fortunately circle in the square has found such an adep 
performer for its revival of the play which opened sunday on 
broadway his name is victor garber and he pretty much lifts this 
production out of the ordinary all by himself 
television audiences may know garber as liberace ii he was the 
king of piano glitz in the second of two recent tv movies based on 
the entertainers life 
new york theateregoers have had a better chance to appraise his 
talent in such diverse offerings as deathtrap sweeney todd 
little me and wenceslas square in most of them the actor 
played supporting roles 
now garber comes into his own as the star of this production he 
portrays dick dudgeon a selfprofessed follower of the devil who 
ends up a man of god by the time the curtain falls 
the setting is revolutionary war new hampshire and the 
playwright is concerned with the hypocrisy of war and peace dicks 
opposite number is the rev anthony anderson a yankee minister who 
also undergoes a conversion of sorts he trades his pulpit for 
pistols before the story is over 
the transformation occurs after the neerdowell is mistaken for 
the minister and is sentenced by the british to hang dick readily 
goes along with the mistake willing to die for another man his 
ultimate act of sacrifice is disrupted by the reverends wife 
judith who at least in this production becomes smitten with the 
imposter 
their romantic attachment is more than hinted at in director 
stephen porters swiftly paced production roxanne hart overdoes the 
emotion as the ministers loyal but bewildered wife she swoons a 
bit too much at the dashing dudgeon 
but then one can sense her disinterest in her minister husband 
played with diffidence by remak ramsay his conversion from boring 
pastor to mighty warrior is unconvincing and seems unexpected 
garbers only real support in what is a large cast comes from 
philip bosco a veteran circle in the square performer bosco plays 
the british gen burgoyne its a small but pivotal role and the 
actor has the wit urbanity and stage presence to carry it off the 
general is shaws voice of common sense a realist who sees what 
will happen to the american colonies and what dudgeon is trying to 
accomplish by his masquerade 
the physical production is respectable if unexciting zack 
browns turntable settings slammed up against one wall are spartan 
a flooring of wooden planks cover the elongated playing area with 
the audience on three sides 
respectable is a good word for the entire production porters 
professional direction never slips even when his two most 
interesting actors are off stage still the play becomes even more 
than that when bosco and particularly garber are on stage its 
these two performers who put this revival of the devils 
disciple on the side of the angels 
other critics such as newsdays leo seligsohn lamented the 
unevenness of the evening for all the stylishness of the production 
at its best porter hasnt wrung the same highquality acting from 
everyone 
howard kissel of the daily news applauded the work of garber and 
hart but complained that the production starts shakily and 
features heavyhanded acting by other principals 
frank rich of the new york times said the work of both stars is 
exemplary just as mr porters staging is largely above reproach 
but this time the gathering of our most lustrous shavian ensemble 
seems a frivolous waste of valuable resources 
clive barnes of the new york post said the production was 
worthy but a little commonplace its pleasures proving all as 
predictable as a fastfood hamburger with most of the trimmings 
</TEXT>
