<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to judge the 
constitutionality of a connecticut law aimed at assuring that beer 
sold in the state costs no more than it does in three neighboring 
states 
the court said it will review a ruling that the 1984 law 
regulating beer prices unduly interfered with interstate commerce 
the justices in 1983 voted 53 in striking down as 
unconstitutional a similar connecticut law 
the earlier law prohibited brewers from selling its brand of beer 
in connecticut at a price higher than the lowest price which it sold 
beer in new york massachusetts or rhode island under that law the 
controlling price was adjusted each month 
the retail price of beer generally has been higher in connecticut 
than in its neighbor states and many connecticut consumers buy beer 
in one of the three neighboring states 
the earlier law was struck down because it was deemed to affect 
the price of beer outside connecticut by locking beer prices in all 
four states for onemonth periods to the level posted in connecticut 
the 1984 connecticut law however stated that the posted 
connecticut beer prices only had to reflect the lowest prices being 
offered at the time of the posting 
the law did not prevent brewers from lowering prices in the three 
neighboring states at any time during the calendar month covered 
by such posting 
beer brewers immediately challenged the 1984 law but a federal 
trial judge upheld it 
the 2nd us circuit court of appeals last june 13 reversed the 
judges ruling and struck down the law 
the realities of beer price regulation in the border state area 
show that connecticuts statute inevitably exercises control over 
the prices set for sales occurring wholly outside its territory 
the appeals court ruled 
accordingly we hold that the amended connecticut beer price 
affirmation provisions directly regulate interstate commerce in 
violation of the constitution it added 
the 2nd circuit courts ruling was appealed by state officials 
and instate beer wholesalers 
the cases are healy vs beer institute 88449 and wine and 
spirits wholesalers vs beer institute 88513 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

