<TEXT>
the supreme court today let stand a ruling that 
the federal voting rights act designed to prevent racial 
discrimination applies to state judicial elections 
the court without comment rejected an appeal by louisiana 
officials who said the law is not intended to cover the judicial 
branch and could impair the independence of judges 
the 5th us circuit court of appeals ruled last february in 
favor of blacks seeking to apply the voter rights law to the 
election of louisiana judges 
the black registered voters said their voting power was diluted 
unlawfully by a system in which two louisiana supreme court justices 
are elected atlarge from a district comprised of four parishes 
the state court has seven justices five of whom are elected from 
singlemember districts the remaining two are elected at large from 
a district comprised of orleans st bernard plaquemines and 
jefferson parishes 
orleans parish has a black population of 55 percent and accounts 
for more than half the population of the fourparish judicial 
district 
the black voters filed a lawsuit to split the four parishes and 
create two singlemember districts thus enhancing the chance that 
orleans parish could elect a black justice to the state court 
the blacks said the atlarge system violates the voting rights 
act of 1965 which is designed to prevent dilution of black voting 
strength 
louisiana officials argued that the law covers only 
representatives of the people namely members of the legislative 
and executive branches of government 
the state officials headed by gov buddy roemer said 
judges should not be representatives the larger the 
constituency the less parochial pressures can be brought to bear 
an advantage to atlarge elections for judges is that judges can 
make the difficult decisions without undue fear of dissatisfaction 
in the electorate 
they added judges have but one constituency the blindfolded 
lady with scales sword and shield 
but the 5th circuit court said the voting rights act is intended 
to be a broad attack on racial discrimination in voting 
clearly judges are candidates for public office the appeals 
court said the act must be interpreted in a broad and 
comprehensive manner in accordance with congressional intent to 
combat racial discrimination of any kind in all voting practices and 
procedures 
judges are elected in most states the louisiana officials said 
there are only eight states delaware hawaii massachusetts new 
hampshire new jersey rhode island vermont and virginia where 
judges are appointed 
the reagan administration supported the 5th circuit courts 
interpretation of the voting rights law 
the natural reading of the term representatives does not 
exclude elected judges in the context of the voting rights act 
the justice department said 
eight states urged the supreme court to hear louisianas appeal 
and decide the issue they are alabama arkansas florida georgia 
illinois mississippi north carolina and texas 
the case is roemer vs chisom 88327 
</TEXT>
