forklifts laden with cases of new beaujolais rushed 
across the tarmac at charles de gaulle airport monday to load the 
wine onto cargo jets bound for bon vivants around the world 
under french law beaujolais primeur is not to be uncorked 
until 1201 am thursday and customs officials kept an eye on 
loading operations to make sure not one drop was consumed before its 
time 
pallets weighing four tons each were lifted through the open nose 
of the air france boeing 747 bound for new york about 72000 
bottles were on a 10 am flight that was delayed two hours because 
of a mechanics strike 
other cartons were destined for portland ore phoenix san 
francisco los angeles ketchum idaho and dozens of other american 
cities 
the us market represents about 10 percent of all beaujolais 
sales west germany switzerland and britain combined take about 60 
percent of the new wine the fastest growing market is japan 
a japan air lines cargo plane was prepared for takeoff carrying 
the pride of dozens of beaujolais vinters while workers rushed to 
load a korean airlines jet parked between the jal and air france 
planes 
for their compatriots far from home air france flights were also 
carrying wine to french overseas territories such as the island of 
reunion 
a delay of a day or two is disastrous according to air 
france spokesman raymond courtat who said the airline would ship 
330 tons of wine on monday and a similar amount tuesday the most 
difficult part is moving fast yet safely 
trucks from the beaujolais region began arriving about 4 am at 
the airport while other trucks carried wine to ports on the english 
channel for shipment to england and still others hit the highway for 
european points 
beaujolais vintners in central france will produce an estimated 
79 million gallons of the simple fruity and relatively inexpensive 
wine 
unlike aged wines primeur beaujolais is ready for drinking about 
six weeks after harvest and meant to be consumed in the months 
immediately after its midnovember release after that it rapidly 
loses its flavor 
the early selling wine accounts for about 55 percent of the 
beaujolais crop this year compared with about 6 percent two decades 
ago 
