<DOCNO> AP881114-0103 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
six educational testing organizations on monday 
unveiled a new code of practices that commits them to strive for 
fairness in tests given students of different races sex or ethnic 
backgrounds 
the voluntary code also commits the test makers to review and 
revise questions to avoid potentially insensitive content or 
language and to offer appropriately modified forms of tests 
to the handicapped 
the code of fair testing practices in education bears the 
endorsement of six companies whose tests are taken by millions of 
american students each year from first grade to graduate school 
the signers of the new code are educational testing service the 
college board the american college testing program ctbmcgraw 
hill the psychological corp and the riverside publishing co 
the code lays out 21 standards for both test developers and test 
users in four areas developing and selecting tests interpreting 
scores striving for fairness and informing test takers 
on fairness it says test developers should strive to make 
tests that are as fair as possible for test takers of different 
races gender ethnic backgrounds or handicapping conditions 
it commits them to investigate the performance of test takers of 
differents races sex and ethnic backgrounds when samples of 
sufficient size are available and to set up procedures to 
ensure that differences in performance are related primarily to the 
skills under assessment rather than to irrelevant factors 
on test selection the code says the test makers should make 
available to qualified users either representative samples or 
complete copies of test questions directions answer sheets 
manuals and score reports 
robert schaeffer a spokesman for fairtest a cambrige mass 
group that is critical of standardized testing said the code 
sounds good in principle but it lacks teeth 
whats needed is public oversight and control of the 
billiondollar testing industry schaeffer said 
everyone wants fair tests he added the question is how do you 
make them fair and who is to judge and who punishes those whose 
tests are nor fair 
the college board sponsors the scholastic aptitude test which is 
made by ets the american college testing program makes the act a 
rival collegeentrance exam ctbmcgraw hill makes both the 
comprehensive test of basic skills and the california achievement 
test the psychological corp makes both the stanford and the 
metropolitan achievement tests riverside publishing makes the iowa 
tests of basic skills 
copies of the code are available from the national council on 
measurement in education 1230 17th st nw washington dc 20036 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
