bad weather forced the air force 
to postpone a plan to explode nearly a half million pounds of 
explosives monday to test a new ordnance storage bunker a base 
spokesman said 
len barry said the enormous blast to test the new hayman igloo 
design could not be conducted during overcast weather because cloud 
cover would reflect the force of the explosion and possibly damage 
buildings in populated areas 
a storm front over northern utah produced heavy cloud cover and 
several inches of snow monday barry said he did not know when the 
test would be rescheduled 
the air force had planned to detonate the explosives on the test 
and training range west of the great salt lake 50 to 60 miles from 
populated areas 
plans had called 450000 pounds of explosive in one igloo to be 
detonated to test the effects on four other igloos built nearby 
the purpose of the test is to determine how far apart the igloos 
should be spaced to prevent an explosion in one from setting off 
others 
the hayman is designed to channel the force of explosion upward 
through the roof and away from other storage bunkers or buildings 
barry said 
the air force has said that under the proper weather conditions 
the test would pose little risk to the public directly or through 
environmental problems 
the state bureau of air quality issued an openburning permit for 
the test after concluding it would not create significant air 
pollution 
barry said the hayman igloo developed by hill air force base 
industrial engineering technician lowell hayman costs only 100000 
to build compared to 500000 for current ammunition storage 
bunkers 
the hayman igloo is made of concrete and steel as is the current 
bunker however the hayman is cheaper because the walls and roof 
are prefabricated and assembled onsite it can be completed in only 
two weeks while the current design built entirely on site 
requires four months 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

