if theres one thing julie wilson has learned 
during her long career singing in nightclubs and hightone places 
like the plaza and the st regis and the algonquin its never count 
on anything 
im a total fatalist says the sophisticated song stylist 
known for her impeccable way with lyrics i feel if its going to 
happen its going to happen if its not its not 
so when peter allen told her nearly five years ago that he would 
write a role for her in his first broadway musical she didnt tell 
anyone 
not a soul miss wilson says you know when you want 
something so much its like the kiss of death if you talk about it 
i didnt open my trap 
her silence and waiting paid off 
miss wilson now is appearing with allen at the mark hellinger 
theater in legs diamond a new musical about the 1920s new york 
gangster allen who wrote the shows music and lyrics also plays 
the famous outlaw miss wilson is flo a woman who fronts a 
nightclub secretly owned by diamond 
they needed a woman of my age and experience to play this role 
someone whos been around the block more than once she laughs 
im the older woman in this show believe me i am the oldie i 
like to say oldie but goodie 
for miss wilson legs diamond is her first broadway musical 
in nearly two decades broadway has only been a part of her show 
business career which began at the age of 17 back in omaha when she 
was chosen miss nebraska since then there have been touring shows 
radio television recordings summer stock and stints in london 
where she appeared in west end editions of kiss me kate south 
pacific and bells are ringing 
but her bread and butter has been nightclubs usually wearing a 
slinky gown and a gardenia perched behind her ear miss wilson has 
sung the best songs of cole porter george gershwin rodgers and 
hart kurt weill stephen sondheim and other broadway writers 
allens material has been a more recent addition she met him for 
the first time in the 1970s but he knew about her long before that 
when he was a kid dancing in australia somebody sent him an 
old record of mine called julie wilson at the st regis she 
says 
those days in the early 1970s were lean years for miss wilson in 
new york suddenly there was no place to sing big clubs were 
closing all over town 
i was fighting for my life she recalls i grabbed whatever 
came my way things like small roles in plays like norman is that 
you in paramus nj 
at the time miss wilson and allen shared the same voice teacher 
keith davis they still do 
i became very aware of peter because my teacher was always 
talking about him and because he had the big hit song i honestly 
love you the singer recalls 
whenever she got a job there would be flowers and a note from 
allen sometimes he and a group of friends would show up to cheer 
her on she attended a lot of his concerts too and they became 
good friends 
then in 1976 she left new york returning to omaha for an 
eightyear sabbatical to take care of her ailing parents and raise 
her two sons when she came back in 1984 to resume her career allen 
showed up at michaels pub an east side nightclub to hear her 
sing it was then that he told her about legs diamond and his 
plans for her 
nothing happened 
a year later she was at her voice teachers studio and ran into 
allen again would you like to hear your song he asked 
allen sat down at the piano and played the music went out of my 
life the song miss wilson sings in legs diamond 
its a little soliloquy she says its a woman singing 
about her loves what happened and why they didnt work out 
then another year went by and miss wilson was asked to perform 
with allen in a workshop production of legs the workshop was 
done in march 1987 the shows producers decided the book by charles 
suppon needed work 
harvey fierstein author of torch song trilogy was brought 
in to help to sharpen some of the characters and make the story 
brighter 
then the show was finally announced to open on broadway in the 
fall of 1988 
but before legs diamond went into rehearsal miss wilson 
found out she was under consideration to replace dolores gray and 
sing the showstopping im still here in the london production 
of follies she told her agent no her heart belonged to 
allen 
i dont want anything else miss wilson told her agent i 
just want to hang out do my club thing and hope that the show will 
go 
she doesnt regret her decision 
im on the boards until they get rid of me she says i 
knew i had to chance it 
