<TEXT>
a year ago the associated press rode along on a 
predawn trip to denver where mexican farm worker alejandro fierro 
wearing his best blue jeans and finest cowboy hat met us 
immigration officers face to face and applied for amnesty after 30 
years of working illegally fierro now boasts a plasticlaminated 
temporary residence card today with only days remaining until the 
deadline for special agricultural workers to apply for the 
governments onetime amnesty fierro is well along the way to 
permanent status and maybe citizenship 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
after three decades of sneaking into the 
united states to earn a living for his family mexican farm worker 
alejandro fierro this year strode across the border upright and 
legal with proof in his pocket that americas new amnesty program 
works 
fierro was 19 in 1958 when he first swam the rio grande and like 
his father and grandfather before him became an illegal alien 
working in the fields of el norte the land up north 
last summer spiffy in a new shirt and polished cowboy boots he 
summoned up his courage and walked into the denver office of the 
us immigration and naturalization service to apply for amnesty 
under the landmark immigration control and reform act of 1986 
that legislation applied to two groups of foreigners living and 
working without permission in this country applications from those 
trying to prove continuous residency in the united states since 
before 1982 totaled 1761766 in the oneyear registration period 
that ended last may 4 
the second category encompasses illegal aliens who have worked 
with perishable crops in certain periods beginning in 1984 
applicants have until nov 30 to seek ins approval as of nov 9 
according to ins figures 1014115 special agricultural workers 
saws had applied for amnesty the approval rate was running at 92 
percent 
fierro is one of the 281112 saws granted temporary resident 
status as of oct 31 thats the first of three steps leading to 
citizenship a move fierro says he will consider seriously in the 
next few years 
sitting in the shade of a big tree on a lunch break in the dawn 
to pastdark colorado onion harvest fierro unsnapped the left 
breast pocket of his western shirt and pulled out the 
plasticlaminated id card he keeps next to his heart 
a90616632 fierrojacobo alejandro says the fine print 
bearer entitled to reside and work in us until card expires not 
eligible for federally funded assistance program expires jan 1 
1991 
the 49yearold father of six speaks no english but he knew the 
meaning of every word on the ins card 
i feel so happy because there is now no problem to find a job 
and i can take a bus said fierro through his friend and 
interpreter reyes perez a us citizen whos worked beside him in 
farmer harry matsushimas fields for years 
the ins card has given fierro back his dignity its also given 
his middleaged legs a rest 
always before beginning his annual migratory ritual in early 
spring fierro would start his stealthy journey to colorado by 
buying five days worth of tortillas canned meat and sweets and 
filling a gallon jug with water then with a spare shirt stuffed in 
his pocket he would pay some strapping mexican teenager 1 to 
carry him piggyback across the rio grande near presidio texas and 
strike out in the darkness on foot 
for five days fierro used to avoid roads and people walking at 
night and hiding by day and finally board a northbound bus only 
when all his instincts told him he was safe from arrest and 
deportation 
not this year 
for the first time i crossed the bridge at el paso which is 
much closer to my home in chihuahua than presidio the american 
inspector looks at my card everything is ok so i go straight 
across the bridge into the united states i didnt have to buy food 
and water i got on a bus in el paso and didnt have to walk 
anywhere fierro said with a big smile 
he was headed for santa fe to work for a few weeks in a 
restaurant kitchen before colorados agricultural season got 
underway thirty miles south of alamogordo nm the border patrol 
pulled the greyhound bus over and put fierros amnesty card to its 
first major test 
they came on and checked the whole bus i was very relieved 
because they let me pass everybody on the bus had papers they 
didnt catch one illegal fierro said 
once in santa fe he said it was easy to find a 350anhour job 
in a restaurant because there are still a lot of illegals around 
but the bosses wont hire them theyre afraid of being caught 
the 1986 legislation aims to prevent illegal aliens from taking 
jobs that ordinarily would be filled by americans and properly 
documented workers the ins estimates as many as 7 million illegal 
aliens are still in the united states 
nationally as of midoctober the ins had issued 3175 warning 
citations and fined 720 businesses more than 2 million for 
violating the new immigration law 
fierro considers his ins card among his most important 
possessions he has proudly showed it to his 80yearold father 
socorro fierro who he says pronounced it a very good thing 
alejandro fierros three daughters live in mexico two of his 
three sons live and work in this country one lives in wichita 
kan and is married to an american the other lives in santa fe and 
has applied for amnesty his third son is home in chihuahua tending 
the 15 cows and small acreage his father has bought with his 
colorado earnings 
i dont know how long i can make him stay home said fierro 
he knows he can have a much better life in el norte and he wants 
to come too 
fierro who lives on about 30 a week and sends more than 
twothirds of his annual 6000 in wages to his wife planned to 
return home when it gets cold but he will come back next year 
and every year after that hes able to hoe harvest and haul onions 
in 1991 when his current id card expires fierro will be 
notified hes eligible to apply for permanent residency if he has 
been an upstanding citizen and a member in good standing of our 
society said ins spokesman duke austin in washington dc 
then he will have to have permanent immigrant status for five 
years before he can apply for naturalization to become a united 
states citizen said austin the earliest that could happen is 
1996 
fierro who was an illegal alien for 30 years said now that its 
actually possible he often wonders what it would like to be an 
american citizen 
it is a big step he said through his interpreter 
especially learning the english but why not i still have many 
years left 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
tad bartimus is the ap mountain states regional 
reporter based in denver 
