notes from america columbia bonnie tyler 
 
theres no denying bonnie tylers voice she could should be 
one of rocks finest female vocalists with her husky growl that 
echoes both janis joplin and tina turner 
the presence of such an extraordinary voice makes notes from 
america worth listening to but unfortunately the material tyler 
uses and the overblown production on the record make it very very 
ordinary 
tyler first hit both pop and country charts 10 years ago with 
its a heartache and five years later had a no 1 single with 
total eclipse of the heart 
since then the welshborn tyler has recorded sparingly on 
notes from america she teams up with producersongwriter 
desmond child who is known for his work with bon jovi and 
aerosmith the aim is to create big hits what results is big and 
it might be a hit but it doesnt do justice to tylers abilities 
the album is overproduced at nearly every turn dont turn 
around for instance is a ballad that starts off as a wonderful 
showcase for tylers tough yet vulnerable voice but as it builds to 
a crescendo as many songs on notes from america do and a choir 
chimes in the core of the song is lost in a tidal wave of sound 
the title track features 50 people corralled on the streets of 
woodstock ny where the album was made to sing backup why only 
50 
other tunes stand up better hide your heart is a hookfilled 
rocker dominated by snarling guitars while take another look at 
my heart is a lighter keyboardbased piece that allows tyler to 
stand out she even does a version of the bee gees to love 
somebody thats better than the original 
one song stands head and shoulders above the rest an old janis 
joplin tune turtle blues is a wonderful bluesrocker that 
shows the vocal phrasing range and power of which tyler is capable 
notes from america sounds like much of the commercial rock 
n roll on the radio these days it might make tyler richer but 
its a shame such a voice isnt singing more memorable music 
by curt anderson associated press writer 
