<TEXT>
sending some patients home immediately after common 
heart catheter tests could reduce the nations medical bills by 
millions of dollars without injuring peoples health a new study 
concludes 
the report estimates that if 15 percent of the 500000 americans 
who undergo this procedure each year were treated as outpatients 
instead of being hospitalized the savings would be 51 million 
some of the savings may already have been realized because many 
doctors in recent years have begun performing the procedure without 
putting their patients in the hospital for a day or two 
the study directed by dr peter c block of massachusetts 
general hospital was published recently in the new england journal 
of medicine 
the doctors compared the experience of 192 patients who were 
randomly assigned to have the procedure as outpatients and 189 
others who were admitted to the hospital for the test no one died 
and there were no significant differences in the need for later 
hospitalization because of complications 
while they concluded that doing the procedure on an outpatient 
basis is feasible and safe they cautioned that only relatively 
young and healthy patients should be treated this way in the study 
patients were not considered for outpatient treatment if they were 
elderly or had a variety of common medical conditions including 
heart failure and high blood pressure 
in an accompanying editorial dr c richard conti of the 
university of florida said the research provides more evidence that 
outpatient procedures are safe and efficient and the results are 
applicable to the general population considered at low risk 
cardiac catherization involves inserting a slender tube through 
an artery into the heart dye is released into the heart and an 
xray camera is used to take movies of blood flowing through the 
heart arteries the procedure is widely used to diagnose heart 
disease 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
navy sailors were less likely to be 
infected by gonorrhea and probably by the aids virus after a 
videotape about aids played constantly on their aircraft carrier 
three days before shore leave a doctor says 
the incidence of gonorrhea among the crew dropped 75 percent 
from 16 to four cases per 1000 men per day said dr william o 
harrison who created the video program before his retirement last 
august as head of the acquired immune deficiency syndrome evaluation 
unit at balboa naval hospital in san diego 
if the incidence of sexually transmitted disease is reduced 
then the likelihood of being exposed to the aids virus is reduced by 
the same amount harrison said during a recent symposium at the 
long beach naval hospital 
harrison cited security rules in declining to name the aircraft 
carrier or ports it visited but said it was one of many ships that 
showed the 70minute video the carriers crew however was the 
only group monitored for sexually transmitted disease rates before 
and after the video was shown 
all navy personnel are tested for hiv the aidscausing human 
immunodeficiency virus before they are sent overseas 
i can substantiate that the education program works said lt 
cmdr richard a weiner flight surgeon on the long beachbased 
ship peleliu which recently returned from the western pacific 
we repeatedly showed the educational videotape made by dr 
harrison and lectured the crew before pulling into port there were 
no hiv positives people who tested positive for signs of aids 
infection and there was a marked decrease in the rate of sexually 
transmitted disease among the crew 
the video describes case histories and how those people 
contracted aids and in a simplified way explains the human immune 
system and how hiv affects the body and discusses the risk of 
catching aids from infected people on active duty harrison said 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
researchers have preliminary evidence that extra 
doses of vitamin e may help elderly people ward off disease by 
boosting the strength of their diseasefighting immune systems 
despite the new evidence however doctors say more research will 
be necessary before they recommend that people take this nutrient to 
stay healthy 
our goals are to identify whether the elderly ought to take 
supplements and to identify the role diet and nutrition play in the 
agerelated diseases and the immune system said dr jeffrey b 
blumberg 
the research was conducted on 32 elderly volunteers at the us 
department of agriculture human nutrition research center on aging 
at tufts university for a month half of them got vitamin e 
supplements while the rest took dummy pills 
skin tests showed marked enhancement of the immune response in 
those getting the vitamin their blood also carried more stimulated 
white cells that indicate the vigor of the immune system 
our results show improvements in immune responses of already 
healthy people said blumberg chief of the lab where the 
research was conducted 
some experts believe that a breakdown of the immune system may 
contribute to the illnesses that afflict old people including 
cancer and infections part of this immune weakness may result from 
oxidation the destructive process that makes iron rust and food 
turn rancid 
vitamin e is an antioxidant it consumes the highly reactive 
chemical molecules known as free radicals that result from 
oxidation in the body levels of antioxidants in the body seem to 
decline with age 
