<DOCNO> AP881114-0225 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme court today ordered a florida court 
to restudy whether that state may tax income derived from the sale 
of oil extracted from the outer continental shelf 
the court sent a case involving shell oil co back to the florida 
supreme court for further study in light of the us supreme courts 
ruling on nov 8 in a case from iowa 
the justices ruled that iowa may tax income derived from oil and 
natural gas taken from the outer continental shelf 
the high court upheld an iowa law that allows a state to impose a 
tax on that portion of a companys income calculated to come from 
the amount of business it does within that state 
in the florida case that states highest court ruled in 1986 
that the florida tax applies to offshore oil refined and sold by an 
oil company within the 50 states after it has been transferred to 
the mainland by pipeline from the offshore wells and platforms 
the state court said only income from oil actually sold on the 
platforms at sea is exempt from the florida tax 
the outer continental shelf is underwater land more than three 
miles off the shore of any state the land is owned by the federal 
government which leases it to private companies 
shell said a 1953 federal law authorizing exploration and 
production of outer continental shelf oil bars states from taxing 
any natural gas or oil derived from the offshore land regardless of 
where the products are sold 
any form of state levy direct or indirect would adversely 
affect the amounts of revenue available to the federal government 
from the offshore leases shell said 
state taxes reduce the value of the federal leases the company 
said 
it added that the florida tax is precisely the result congress 
attempted to forbid in exempting the oil from state taxes 
the florida department of revenue imposed the tax on a portion of 
shell oils profits based on a complex formula designed to take into 
account what percentage of the companys national business occurs in 
florida 
the natural gas extracted by shell was not affected by the case 
because it is transferred to other companies that rent space on 
shells offshore platforms and was not carried by pipeline to the 
mainland before sale 
the supreme court in 1981 struck down a louisiana tax on natural 
gas that passes through the state on its way to consumers in other 
states the court said the louisiana tax interferes with interstate 
commerce and with the authority vested in the federal energy 
regulatory commission 
the case is shell oil vs florida 861593 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

